CTFT
====
	x(t)=1/(2 pi)\integral_(-inf)^(inf) X(w) e^(iwt) dw
	X(t)=\integral_(-inf)^(inf) x(t) e^(-iwt) dw


	1. If x(t) is real, X*(w)=X(-w)
	2. x(t) <------> X(w)
	3. x(t-T) <----> e^(-iwT)X(w)
	4. x(t)e^(iWt) <----> X(w-W)

	x(t)cos(Wt)=(1/2)x(t)(e^(iWt)+e^(-iWt))=(1/2)(x(t)e^(iWt)+x(t)e^(-iWt)) <--------> (1/2)(X(w-W)+X(w+W)) (Linearity!!)

	x(t) ---> LTI ---> y(t)

	X(w) ---> Y(w) = H(w)X(w)

	so y(t)=1/(2 pi) \integral_(-infinity)^(infinity) X(w)H(w)e^(iwt) dw

	Can take CTFT of aperiodic signal, but doing so requires Dirac Deltas.
		In EE20, we use CFT for aperiodic, but CTFT for periodic.
	
	Generalization of Impulse Reponse to Continuous Time
		Recall: In Discrete Time, y(n)=(h*x)(n)
									  =\sum_(k=-inf)^(inf) h(k)x(n-k)
		
		In Continuous Time, y(t)=(h*x)(t)
								=\integral_(-inf)^(inf) h(s)x(t-s) ds

	y(t)=1/T \integral_(t-T)^(t) x(\tau) d\tau

	h(t)=?

	h(t)={1/T, 0<t<T, 0 else}

	What is the relationship between h(t) and H(w) for a LTI system?

	H(w) : e^(iwt) --> H(w)e^(iwt)

	It is the CTFT!

	Proof:
		y(t)=\integral_(-infinity)^(infinity) h(s)e^(iw(t-s)) ds
		y(t)= e^(iwt) \integral_(-infinity)^(infinity) h(s)e^(-iws) ds
		FT{h(t)}=H(w)
	
	Representation gets more complicated with two path-channel: y(t)=x(t-T1)+x(t-T2)

	There are two kinds of CT impulse responses: those with a finite number of echoes, and those with an infinite number of echoes.

MOAR Communication Channel!!
============================
	bits ----> Baseband DSP ----> D/A ----> x cos(w_c t) ----> LTI ----> x cos(w_c t) ----> A/D ----> Baseband DSP ----> bits

	W = bandwidth

	----> x cos(w_c t) ----> LTI ----> x cos(w_c t) ---->

	Frequency goes from range of +/- W/2 about 0 to +/-W/2 about +/-W about w_c

	Second x cos(w_c t) shifts w_c back to 0 and 2w_c
